    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md grid--centered-sm" data-aos="fade-up">
      <h4>Connecting with people that search</h4>
      <p>When someone searches, we wanted to provide a way for that person to learn about Foundation Funds. However, we didn’t want to distract the person from the task at hand – finding the thing that they searched for. For that reason, we included a sidebar that was outside the search result listings.</p>
      <p>Our ideal was to show a specific Fund based on what was being searched (IE if someone searched for a nonprofit related to the environment we could show the Mitigate Climate Change Foundation Fund). However, after talking with our engineers we discovered that this would be a heavy lift. It would involve understanding the search query, and mapping that to one of the 7 Foundation Funds. Based on our discussion of scope earlier on, we decided to keep this idea in our pocket for a later iteration.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="image-full__wrapper image-full--foundation-funds grid--max" data-aos="fade-up">
      <img src="../images/cs-foundation-fund/search-01.jpg" class="image-full__img" alt="Product design mockup of search page">
    </div>

    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md grid--centered-sm" data-aos="fade-up">
      <h4>Listing all of the Foundation Funds</h4>
      <p>On the index page of Foundation Funds we prominently listed each Fund and provided a navigation at top so that people could see all of the options in one view. This would make it faster for people to identify a cause they care about. Clicking an item in the navigation scrolls the user to the appropriate Fund in the list.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="image-full__wrapper image-full--foundation-funds grid--max image-grid" data-aos="fade-up">
