      <h5>Feedback</h5>
      <h3>Learn with prototypes</h3>
      <p>I built a round of prototypes to gain alignment internally and to use as conversation starters with Fund managers and donors. We knew, however, that receiving feedback on an idea is very different than what would happen when someone is on their own deciding whether or not to pull out their credit card. This is especially true with giving. People don’t want to come off as insensitive when hypothetically deciding whether they would support something.</p>
      <p>With that in mind, we used prototypes to see if there were any blindspots that we hadn’t considered. At the same time, our goal was to get the product up and running as fast as possible so that we could collect real, actionable data.</p>
      <p>This is an early prototype we used to guide discussions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="image-full__wrapper image-full--foundation-funds grid--max" data-aos="fade-up">
      <a href="https://invis.io/V5VB6N2MHEU#/398248729_Foundation_Funds_-_03b" target="_blank"><img src="../images/cs-foundation-fund/prototype-01.jpg" alt="Product design prototype of Foundation Funds" class="image-full__img"></a>
    </div>

    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md grid--centered-sm" data-aos="fade-up">
      <p>Something we learned was that the knowledge and emotion that the Fund Managers shared when speaking with our team was difficult to replicate. We thought it could be interesting to test having a video or recording on each Fund with the expert. This could be an engaging way to tell the story behind a Fund. This idea was saved for a later round of testing.</p>
    </div>
  </section>


  <section class="grid">
    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md grid--centered-sm" data-aos="fade-up">
      <h5>Development</h5>
      <h3>Building together</h3>
      <p>I partnered with one developer who led the technical implementation. Because the full team was involved in earlier stages, when it came to implementation we could hit the ground running. I worked directly with them to break the work into the various scopes, break features into smaller chunks, QA work during implementation, and help with the front-end.</p>
      <p>When work was deployed, I could pull the latest and push updates directly. For example, if a UI component needed work or copy needed wordsmithing I would do that in code. No frustrated designer who doesn’t feel in control of the final product and no frustrated developer digging through pixel specs.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="grid">
    <div class="case-study__content-wrapper--md grid--centered-sm" data-aos="fade-up">
      <h5>Shipping</h5>
      <h3>And moving forward...</h3>
      <p>With this project we were seeing if people would shift their giving behavior.  “I know you weren’t planning to give here, but once you see the impact you can make we think you’ll be interested.” We saw that there was an interest (85% of donors say they care about nonprofit performance). And we knew that best knowledge of where to give and how to give was held in Foundations or cause area experts. So, what happened?</p>
      <p>To test this project, we launched six Foundation Funds. Each Fund was given a goal ranging from $20,000 to $30,000 to gauge interest. There were a mix of causes - some Funds were focused on specific locations (Fight Poverty in the Bay Area) and others were focused on broader issue areas (Mitigate global climate change).</p>
      <p>We saw Funds with broader focus areas reach  and exceed their goals. For example Mitigate Climate Change’s initial goal of $30,000 was surpassed in the first few months and received over $50,000.</p>
      <p>Location specific Funds received less support, likely due to the narrower set of potential donors.</p>
      <blockquote>That several thousand people responded positively enough to donate was a leading light. At the same time, we learned several things that would shape future projects.</blockquote>
      <p>Location specific Funds had the potential of gaining strong support from people in the area. Our challenge was awareness. We needed to develop ways to connect with people in these locations so that they would be aware of this way to give. Our user base was spread around the U.S. and around the world, which is why we found more support towards boarder cause areas.</p>
      <p>This project helped people give by letting them lean on others’ expertise. It reduced the burden of ‘where do I give?’. However, it didn’t address getting people in the door in the first place. This was a core focus for several future projects – and our largest learning. We could make it easier for people to give effectively, but they need to decide to give in the first place.</p>
    </div>
  </section>


